WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.800
So I was initially going to talk about buy and try specifics, but apparently someone else is going to talk about try specifics.

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:08.260
So that gave me extra two minutes. So, all right, we're good.

00:00:09.700 --> 00:00:14.480
So let me just put it in context. Right. So Vinay said, you know, he showed you the history of this meeting.

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:23.000
Let's talk about the history of buy specifics. So we opened the first buy specific trial around 2019 at City of Hope.

00:00:24.100 --> 00:00:39.040
And I think all of the people at this table open and can also say we had low expectations and they so surpassed our expectations in terms of having response rates of about 60 percent of people with a median of five prior lines of therapy.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:44.120
So as a single agent, something we'd really never seen. So that was 2019.

00:00:45.100 --> 00:00:51.540
Fast forward 2022 to, you know, 23 when these drugs got approved, we got to use them in more and more patients.

00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:53.840
We started to understand the complexities.

00:00:54.100 --> 00:00:56.840
Some of the complexities, why are patients relapsing?

00:00:57.100 --> 00:01:00.480
This concept of antigen escape, which hopefully someone will speak to today.

00:01:01.100 --> 00:01:08.800
Tumor heterogeneity, extramedullary disease, as well as some of the on target off tumor toxicities.

00:01:08.940 --> 00:01:10.440
And how do we manage those better?

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:16.940
So now fast forward four years, 2026, where are we with buy specifics?

00:01:16.940 --> 00:01:19.060
Well, hopefully we're getting a lot better at using them.

00:01:19.280 --> 00:01:23.940
But as Tom already did a bunch of my slides, so thank you for that, Tom, in terms of early.

00:01:24.100 --> 00:01:26.220
Clear lines of therapy and combinations.

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:28.460
That's really the future of our therapy.

00:01:29.220 --> 00:01:32.980
So let's start with majestic seven front line settings.

00:01:32.980 --> 00:01:35.480
So this is probably the real question there.

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:46.280
Can we do better in patients not intended for transplant beyond really what I would say has been our standard for many, many years of DRD?

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:49.760
So this was looking at both tech and TAL.

00:01:49.900 --> 00:01:54.060
They did a safety run in and now we're in the main part of the trial.

00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:55.960
Tech DR, TAL, DR, DRD.

00:01:56.120 --> 00:01:59.140
So this trial is ongoing and we're waiting to see results.

00:01:59.140 --> 00:02:01.560
I can tell you, I don't know if you guys have it open.

00:02:01.960 --> 00:02:05.960
Everyone we've put on the buy specific arms, you know, has responded.

00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:11.600
So, you know, of course, now we're thinking about toxicity, quality of life and PFS.

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:15.140
But again, I think this is going to be the future, certainly.

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:18.940
Now, let's move on to the next.

00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:22.780
Here you can see right now, this was the safety run and already very impressive.

00:02:23.020 --> 00:02:23.940
Ninety two percent.

00:02:24.100 --> 00:02:27.460
Sixty percent of patients getting a stringent CR.

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:32.460
I mean, that's equivalent to what you can do with quad induction and a single transplant.

00:02:32.640 --> 00:02:33.560
So pretty impressive.

00:02:34.980 --> 00:02:36.940
Let's talk about tech five now.

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:41.500
So looking at this in the context of stem cell transplant.

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:43.020
So here again, you see tech.

00:02:43.400 --> 00:02:47.160
I find this trial interesting because you give tech weekly, you give tech Q four weeks.

00:02:47.160 --> 00:02:53.240
So understanding how do we play with these drugs to get less toxicity but maintain efficacy?

00:02:54.100 --> 00:02:55.620
And Tom said life support.

00:02:55.780 --> 00:03:03.560
This is one trial which sort of brings me to that question about life support for transplant, because look at after induction.

00:03:03.560 --> 00:03:15.140
If you get 100 percent response rate, you have to ask yourself, what is the transplant adding on top of this in terms of 100 percent of patients getting not just response, but MRD negative?

00:03:15.140 --> 00:03:22.500
So I think this, again, is also going to be very interesting to us as this trial evolves in terms of looking at durability of these responses.

00:03:22.980 --> 00:03:23.980
Of course, we can't use any of these.

00:03:23.980 --> 00:03:24.920
We can't use any of those yet.

00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:27.720
That's still in the investigational phase.

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:29.200
What can we use?

00:03:29.780 --> 00:03:34.080
So, of course, March of this year, tech DARA was approved.

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:36.300
And we have the CAR-T queen here.

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:39.680
So I'm not ready to say that CAR-T is on life support.

00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:47.120
But let me point out tech three.

00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:53.860
So the key parts of tech three, they excluded patients had prior BCMA therapy and they excluded patients.

00:03:53.860 --> 00:03:55.820
Who were refractory to CD38.

00:03:55.820 --> 00:04:04.900
And so and of course, that is because the control arm was DPD or DBD, about five percent of patients ended up having CD38 exposure.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:08.220
So that for us really becomes the main question of this trial.

00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:11.920
If you just look at the schedule, I do want to point out a couple of things.

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:14.920
The good thing, they mirrored the DARA schedule.

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:17.420
So eventually the tech also became monthly.

00:04:17.420 --> 00:04:21.980
The not so good thing is this was still treat to disease progression.

00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:23.740
And you remember Tom showed you cure.

00:04:23.740 --> 00:04:25.880
Cure was off therapy.

00:04:25.880 --> 00:04:28.180
So how do we put this into that context?

00:04:28.180 --> 00:04:30.160
We're going to have to see.

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:35.200
But of course, my care is not as good at tech, Leal, but it's pretty darn good.

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:40.720
I mean, like in first relapse, these are the kind of patients that we would consider for CAR-T.

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:47.980
So, you know, I'm just saying, you know, off the shelf and easy regimen to give.

00:04:47.980 --> 00:04:51.220
So something to think about now.

00:04:51.220 --> 00:04:53.620
And of course, March 5th, this drug was a.

00:04:53.620 --> 00:04:55.180
This combination was approved.

00:04:55.180 --> 00:04:57.160
So I'm glad we don't have a debate.

00:04:57.160 --> 00:05:00.940
It would be interesting to see which side people fall on.

00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:03.760
The other thing I want to say is combination therapy.

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:07.840
Right. And I know you guys use this a lot at UCSF because we all share the same patients.

00:05:07.840 --> 00:05:10.960
We do the same consults and we go back and forth.

00:05:10.960 --> 00:05:14.040
And this is a combination that many of us are using.

00:05:14.040 --> 00:05:17.240
We're using Taldarapam, we're using Tectarapam.

00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:22.100
And you can see here from the TRIM2 data that you do get higher response rates.

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:23.500
So we tend to use these combinations.

00:05:23.500 --> 00:05:29.680
And people who have much more refractory, difficult to treat disease, and of course,

00:05:29.680 --> 00:05:34.460
it's not just with teclastamab, it's with Elra, it's with Linvo, everyone is sort of

00:05:34.460 --> 00:05:35.460
doing this.

00:05:35.460 --> 00:05:39.860
And you can see response rates do get higher, but up to the 80% range when you use these

00:05:39.860 --> 00:05:43.260
combination therapies.

00:05:43.260 --> 00:05:47.840
And then of course, GPRC, let's not forget that one, as Dr. Chari says, he loves all

00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:49.020
his children equally.

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:52.780
So this is Talquetamab, the GPRC targeting drug.

00:05:52.780 --> 00:05:53.380
Same idea.

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:59.660
Combination therapy, Taldara that Dr. Chari reported on, you can see response rate 70%

00:05:59.660 --> 00:06:00.660
to 80%.

00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:05.020
I actually found the Tal checkpoint inhibitor really interesting.

00:06:05.020 --> 00:06:08.860
I wish that had moved forward because many of us think that it would actually be one

00:06:08.860 --> 00:06:12.420
of the best partners to a bispecific.

00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:17.640
Taltec, of course, a redirect study showed, especially in extramedullary disease, which

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:23.260
is the particularly hard to treat group for us, very high response rates, and then Talpalminab.

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:24.800
Another favorite combination.

00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:32.000
So let me just talk about Taltec that Dr. Usmani presented at ASH combination trial and looking

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:33.000
truly at EMDs.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:39.080
So in the myeloma world, EMD is controversial because you have to define it properly.

00:06:39.080 --> 00:06:42.180
Is it paramedullary or is it extramedullary?

00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:46.660
And this, we all think extramedullary disease is really the poor actor.

00:06:46.660 --> 00:06:52.140
And you can see they look, they were very specific in this and they showed incredibly

00:06:52.140 --> 00:06:53.140
high response rates.

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:56.840
And those response rates seem to be holding up.

00:06:56.840 --> 00:07:01.900
And so here again, I think this is very promising data for us because even with CAR-T, as Dr.

00:07:01.900 --> 00:07:06.760
Patel can tell you, this is a tough group of patients and I'm already running over.

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:11.140
So let me just finish bispecifics in 2026 are evolving.

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:13.960
We're moving them to earlier lines of therapy.

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:16.200
We're using combinations.

00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:21.140
The future I think is really going to be giving them for fixed duration and certainly using

00:07:21.140 --> 00:07:23.020
them in the frontline setting.

00:07:23.020 --> 00:07:30.220
And the transplant question, I think I totally agree will become less and less something

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:31.440
we use frontline.

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:32.940
So thank you.
